                                                <p><name type="person"><hi rend="initialcap">L</hi>EAP, <hi rend="initialcap">J</hi>OHN <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>.</name>, Private, <name type="organization">Co. G, 28th New Jersey</name>,
                                                                aged 43 years.  <name type="BATTLE" key="4">Fredericksburg</name>, <date type="injury" when="1862-12-13">December 13th,
                                                                                1862</date>.  Gunshot fracture of frontal bone by round
                                                  ball.  <name type="place" key="WASHINGTON">Washington</name> and <name type="place">Philadelphia</name> hospitals.  Spiculæ of bone removed by <choice><orig>crucial</orig><reg>cruciate</reg></choice> incision. Difficulty of micturition, and pain in temples and nape of neck.  Discharged <date type="servicedischarge" when="1863-03-06">March 6th, 1863</date>.  <date type="pension" when="1869-09-30">September 30th, 1869</date>, <name type="person">Examiner James E. Armstrong, M. D.</name>, reports that the missile still remains
                                                  within the cavity, and is supposed to be near the
                                                  base of the brain.²  His memory and sight are
                                                                <choice><orig>impared</orig><reg>impaired</reg></choice>, and he is subject to attacks of vertigo
                                                                and syncope.</p>
                                                <p>² See the series of nineteen cases on p. 193, <hi rend="italic">et seq.</hi>, with which this would have been grouped had the evidence been more satisfactory.</p>                                                
